{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a407d067-c444-4c3e-b39e-ac2214888bb2","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform the VSTest flags are replaced by platform-native switches. Pass them after `--` so `dotnet test` forwards them to the new runner:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n\n| Feature | Package |\n|---|---|\n| TRX reports | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| Code coverage | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| Crash dumps | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| Hang dumps | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\n**Key flag mappings:**\n\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m`\n- `--filter` syntax is unchanged","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36de202d-b427-4ae5-bba3-3b70d353a563","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n1. `dotnet test` still works but the underlying runner changes\n2. Filter syntax changes: `--filter` becomes `--filter` (same) or `--test-filter`\n3. Logger: `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n4. Code coverage: `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` becomes `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n\n\n5. Blame and hang detection flags also change\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` acts as a bridge to the new runner, though on .NET 8 specifically, the integration might be less seamless than in .NET 9 where it's more fully supported. I might need to clarify whether the user should stick with `dotnet test` or run the test executable directly.\n\nThe CLI arguments shift significantly across the board. Filter syntax stays similar, but logging and diagnostics require different flags and corresponding extension packages. Code coverage moves from the `--collect` syntax to `--coverage` with format options, crash dumps use `--crashdump` instead of `--blame-crash`, and hang detection becomes `--hangdump` with `--hangdump-timeout` replacing the blame-hang variants. Each of these diagnostic features needs its own extension package installed. Completing the NuGet package list for HangDump support. I should note that the filter syntax varies by framework—MSTest uses `TestCategory` while xUnit uses `Category` as the trait name—but since the user didn't specify which framework they're using, I'll keep the answer concise and mention that Microsoft.Testing.Platform handles similar filter syntax across frameworks.","outputTokens":1161,"requestId":"7C1E:12D387:26196DB:2A2E5AA:69F94025"},"id":"5e1df3d0-157f-4a9d-b71e-da810e941309","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:56:25.870Z","parentId":"3dec4a57-5cc0-42fd-8ca9-dcebfc47854b"}
